Though Ho- race in his odes uses the construction with the subjunctive. in the first clause, and future in the second (C. iii. 3. 7), he is not likely to have done it here. Bentley edits ‘noles' and ‘veniet. ’‚—Horace in winding up his discourse, stops the lips of his opponents with a sally of good humour, which they would find it hard ·to resist. He says if they will not make allowance for this little sin of his (that of taking notes of his neighbours' vices), he will brin a host of sinners (poets) as bad as himse ‚ and, like the proselytizing Jews, they will attack them till they have made conver-ts and poets of them all. ‘ Multo plures sumus’ means ‘ there are many besides me.' [On the proselytism of the Jews Ritter quotes Tacit. Hist. v. 5, and Cicero, Pro Flacco, c. 28.
